    {
      "id": "/page/0/TextInlineMath/16",
      "block_type": "TextInlineMath",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"TextInlineMath\">The expected discounted penalty function, introduced by Gerber and Shiu in [6], captures the joint distribution of three random variables related to ruin; the time of ruin <math display=\"inline\">T</math>, the surplus immediately prior to ruin <math display=\"inline\">U(T^{-})</math>, a <b>Solvency</b> early warning, and the severity of the deficit at ruin <math display=\"inline\">|U(T)|</math>, a recovery test measure. Also called the Gerber-Shiu <math display=\"inline\">(G-S)</math><i>function</i>, the expected discounted penalty function is defined as</p>",
      "page": 229,
      "polygon": [
        [
          301.24556962025315,
          265.32405566600397
        ],
        [
          513.3164556962025,
          265.32405566600397
